<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900801-0015</DOCNO><DOCID>900801-0015.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Stalinism-Steeped Albania   Allows Foreign Investment   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>08/01/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><CO>   EUROP</CO><IN>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)</IN><LP>   VIENNA -- Communist Albania announced it will permitforeign investment and joint ventures. It also decreedlimited freedom to stage public demonstrations.   The new economic measures decreed by the Tirana leadershipappeared designed to alleviate economic backwardness, providetechnical know-how, improve living conditions and circumventa ban on foreign credits.</LP><TEXT>   The decrees were approved by the presidium of the People'sAssembly and reported by the state news agency ATA only weeksafter some 5,000 Albanians, holed up in foreign embassies,were allowed to emigrate from Albania, the poorest country inEurope and a lone stronghold of Stalinism.   &quot;Foreign embassies, firms or individuals or Albaniansresiding abroad can make investments or carry out relatedeconomic activities,&quot; said a decree issued on &quot;the protectionof foreign investments in the People's Socialist Republic ofAlbania.&quot;   While the official announcement didn't specificallymention joint ventures, it said that in Albania &quot;enterpriseswith participation of foreign capital can carry out theireconomic activity in various sectors of the economy.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>